CARA MEMBUAT ES BATU
Bahan-bahan :
1. Air matang  500 gr
2. Kantong plastik ukuran  500 gr
3. Kulkas atau Freezer  (segala merek) 
4. Karet gelang 
Cara membuatnya : 
1. Masukan air matang ke dalam plastik
2.Ikat ujungnya dgn karet gelang dgn erat
3. Masukan ke dlm kulkas/freezer
4. Tunggu beberapa jam sampai air mengeras (jd batu) 
Selamat mencoba.

If you know seventeen, synchronisation doesnt even seem to be the main highlight for this choreography. For me its how they acted out the lyrics so well while still staying on beat. For most groups its either the lyrics or the beat. If you read the lyrics and then see the choreography, its clearly visible how well they have encoded the actions and the attempts of keeping yourself in control, not to crumble down 2:12 but act as if its okay. How they pull their legs in order to collect themself at one point 1:08, heck even the way they walk during 1:27 alone says a lot about the meaning of song, theres desperation and a sense of urgency at 1:48, the part at 2:26 is just love, they get down on their knees as if they have lost everything with the realization and then theres strong dancing and then again they stand facing the sky and then they look down again. 
Throughout the choreo, they're controlling and caging themselves and are walking on thin ice with very calculated movements knowing that a little more freedom and truth to their actions will only make them lose it completely. I can literally go about it all day but im not good with words. I love this song so much i swear i do, the lyrics, the melody, the choreography, the expression EVERYTHING.

author: @epic-k1217
text: This video and Seventeen will forever own the most precious corner of my heart.  Almost two years ago, this was my introduction into the wonderful and captivating universe of K-pop.  From the very first line of the song , I felt the sweet sadness of the lyrics (I certainly had NO idea what they were singing about) and the dancing conveyed an inner struggle of emotions in a way that was captivating.  The looks, the tones, the harmonies, the movements, and well, gotta be honest, the members themselves were all so flawless.  And even though I knew it was born from countless hours of practice and monotonous repetition, it struck me how genuine it still felt.  I got sucked under the Hallyu wave so hard that I still haven't come up for air.  I began studying K-pop culture, then Korean culture, then Korean, and of course consuming more K-pop than any grown adult my age should be comfortable admitting to.  And it all began to change me...there is some magic that began to work and connect to my inner self and set me free.  I have come to live life more brightly, fully confident and at peace with myself and the world around me thanks to this remarkable journey. author: @bubulia
text: Okay this is going to be along cheesy rant but I absolutely love this group so much and I can never find the words to express me love and support for them. Seventeen is the only kpop group in the history of my kpop career that I have loved so deeply. I love all the members, all the songs, all their albums and merch. Before svt I was never able to fully like a kpop group to the point of wanting to get to know the members and their personalities or buy an album. The first time I saw the Adore U mv something inside me told me to explore them further and I am so blessed that I did. I remember the exact moment when I fell in love with them was when I saw the Adore U live vid and at the end of the choreo they did this falling over leg move and I just remembered how absolutely in snyc and lively in performance was. It was at that exact moment when I finally realized how other fans felt about their bias groups that I never experienced. It was from then on that I have given my undivided attention and unwavering support for seventeen and they have NEVER ceased to impress me with their energy, motivation, talent and dedication. Sounds stupid and over the top but their music has really helped me through though times when I felt so low in life. The fact that they were rookies in a small company and are now spoken about with some of the best in the industry such as BTS and EXO is incredible. Watching the interaction and support between members really makes me feel like they've found where they belong and are living their dreams at the moment fully with wonderful friends. Hearing about them working themselves to the point of injury makes me feel worried but also a sense of overflowing pride for these 13 boys. I wish nothing but love, happiness, prosperity and success for these boys and when they go on their tour, I want them to see how many hearts they've touched all over the world with their blood sweat and tears.

author: @hanahhanah1341
text:
I love the song, the choreo, everything. I've been wanting to indulge myself into them and be a carat for the longest time ever since they debuted but I can't do so because I'm still scared after taorishan happened with EXO. I loved them so hard that I'm still broken right now. I'm so scared that history will repeat itself. I love svt but I just can't bring myself to fully love them.

Not to mention this really beautiful fandom. I was going through some of the comments and dude I can't. I see the early (beautiful) stages of every fandom where it's all positive and I love that. There are only a few fandoms which have carried out that stage even until their artist got old. And I wish carat will be one of those. I'm a multifandom fan myself so I've seen lots of different fandoms and carat is one of the best.

I hope someday I can bring myself to overcome my 'trauma' (😂) and love these boys with all my harteu.

FIGHTING SEVENTEEN! FIGHTING CARATS!

author: @radish1395
text:
So the thing about this choreography is that it is not only different than what Hosh and their choreographer have come up with in the past, it also adds to the story and the emotion of the song. I'm not an expert on dance but I really like when I see something in the performance aspect of groups, like I do here. The song is about heartbreak, but I want to think there is a little more to it, a little more personal (like when you're heartbroken about anything, not just a love ending).

The movements are shaky, almost robotic, in the choruw,  and when you experience heartbreak but you're trying to hide it, you tend to lose yourself and slip into a "default mode" of yourself. The characters they're playing for these performances are fighting the tears, but that takes a lot of effort, so they're not themselves. 

But in the verses, they move fluidly (and sadly, tbh) because they're alone, essentially. They're embracing what they're feeling more. This is especially true for Woozi's modern-esque moves and Coupsy/Jeonghan walking under the (handsome) streetlamps. 

Then the bridge (where Wonwoo steals the show; this is his era y'all), Meanie are moving through the boys and I think that represents all the times you have to pretend to be okay when you're hurting. You move around and navigate until you're alone again. And it's just hard... until you break and you crumble (them falling to their knees in the last chorus).

The last chorus is choppy and not as robotic... that's why you break, when you need to let yourself cry, feel, admit what's going on with you, even to yourself. 

THIS IS JUST ME OKAY I COULD BE WRONG BUT HOSH LOVES DANCE TOO MUCH NOT TO TAKE ADVANTAGE OF STORYTELLING IN A SONG LIKE THIS
